f the property)."]}]},{"name":"Garlande","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>gerlond</i>, <i>ger(e)land</i>, <i>garlond</i> ‘metal chaplet, crown, coronet; wreath’, probably a nickname denoting a habitual wearer of such items, or a metonymic occupational name for a maker of them.","English: perhaps from the Old French personal name <i>Gerland</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Garuland</i>, probably from <i>garw-</i> ‘war-gear; prepared(ness)’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’; the first element of the French name may instead be from a name beginning with <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>lond</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>gāra</i> + <i>land</i>, <i>lond</i>), for someone who lived ‘(at the) triangular piece of land’. Compare   Garfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerland","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Garland  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Garfield","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country, field’ (Old English <i>gār</i> + <i>feld</i>), for someone who lived by a triangular piece of land.","English: alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Carville   (a name of Norman origin), with excrescent final <i>-d</i>.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Gartland","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Garland  .","Irish (northern Leinster and southern Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Gearnúin</b>, a patronymic from the Norman personal name   Gernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Garlande IV was born in 1125, in Europe, his father, Guillaume de Garlande III Anseau, was 25 and his mother, Agnès Nanteuil, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Idoine DE CHAUMONT. He died in 1191, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1125–1191":"1125–1191","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1130–1208":"1130–1208","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1100–1132":"1100–1132","1105–1180":"1105–1180","1132":"1132","environ 1160":"umbes 1160","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","environ 1180":"umbes 1180","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1105":"1105","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1100":"1100","1208":"1208","Europe":"Europe","Europa":"Europe","Ivry-La-Bataille, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Ivry-la-Bataille, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1125–1191":"1125–1191","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1130–1208":"1130–1208","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1100–1132":"1100–1132","1105–1180":"1105–1180","1132":"1132","environ 1160":"noin 1160","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","environ 1180":"noin 1180","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1105":"1105","1125":"1125","1200":"1200","1100":"1100","1208":"1208","Europe":"Europe","Europa":"Europe","Ivry-La-Bataille, Eure, Haute-Normandie, France":"Ivry-la-Bataille, Eure, Haute-Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1125–1191":"1125–1191","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1130–1208":"1130–1208","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1100–1